  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <p><strong>How long should I give a therapist before deciding they're not right?</strong></p>
  <p>Give it at least 4–6 sessions before making a judgment. First sessions are inherently more awkward; the relationship builds over time. That said, if you have a strong negative gut response after the first session — something felt wrong, not just uncomfortable — trust that.</p>
  <p><strong>Is it rude to switch therapists?</strong></p>
  <p>No. Therapists expect this and professional standards support it. You can simply not rebook, or you can say directly: "I don't think this is the right fit for me." A good therapist will thank you for the honesty and may even help you find someone better suited.</p>
  <p><strong>Do I have to tell my old therapist I'm switching?</strong></p>
  <p>It's courteous to let them know, but not required. An email saying "I'm not going to continue with sessions" is sufficient. You don't owe an explanation.</p>
  <p><strong>What if I've tried multiple therapists and none have helped?</strong></p>
  <p>Consider whether the issue is fit, approach, or engagement. Did you try different modalities (CBT vs. psychodynamic)? Did you try therapists who specialize in your specific concern? Were you fully engaged in the process? If you're unsure, a consultation with a senior clinician or a psychiatrist to assess whether medication might help alongside therapy could be valuable.</p>
